The '''male infertility crisis''' is a term used by the popular media to describe the rapid decrease in [[sperm quality]], and consequential problems with [[male infertility]], seen over the 40 year period starting in the late 1970s.<ref name=":0">{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.theguardian.com/science/2017/jul/29/infertility-crisis-sperm-counts-halved|title=The infertility crisis is beyond doubt. Now scientists must find the cause|last=McKie|first=Robin|date=2017-07-29|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-10-10}}</ref> Over that time period, the number of viable sperm in men in [[Australia]], [[Europe]], [[New Zealand]] and [[North America]] has roughly halved, falling at a rate of 1.4% per year.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Levine|first=Hagai|last2=Jørgensen|first2=Niels|last3=Martino-Andrade|first3=Anderson|last4=Mendiola|first4=Jaime|last5=Weksler-Derri|first5=Dan|last6=Mindlis|first6=Irina|last7=Pinotti|first7=Rachel|last8=Swan|first8=Shanna H|date=2017-07-25|title=Temporal trends in sperm count: a systematic review and meta-regression analysis|url=https://academic.oup.com/humupd/article-abstract/23/6/646/4035689?redirectedFrom=fulltext|journal=Human Reproduction Update|language=en|volume=23|issue=6|pages=646–659|doi=10.1093/humupd/dmx022|pmid=28981654|issn=1355-4786}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2017/jul/25/sperm-counts-among-western-men-have-halved-in-last-40-years-study|title=Sperm counts among western men have halved in last 40 years – study|last=Davis|first=Nicola|date=2017-07-25|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-10-10}}</ref> This reduction has not been seen in other parts of the world.<ref name="indy-a7859491">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/sperm-count-west-men-health-drop-60-per-cent-years-modern-life-a7859491.html|title=Western men's sperm counts plunge 60% in 40 years due to 'modern life'|last=Johnston|first=Ian|date=25 July 2017|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en-GB}}</ref> A number of hypotheses have been put forward for the causes of the decline, including lifestyle factors and the presence of [[endocrine disruptor|hormone-disrupting chemicals]] in the environment.<ref name=indy-a7859491/>
== Mass media coverage == The phenomenon has been the subject of study for some years, starting with a 1992 paper by Skakkebaek et al.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/2017/09/22/male-infertility-crisis-experts-663074.html|title=The male infertility crisis: Who's killing America's sperm?|last=Walsh|first=Bryan|date=2017-09-12|work=Newsweek|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Carlsen|first=E.|last2=Giwercman|first2=A.|last3=Keiding|first3=N.|last4=Skakkebaek|first4=N. E.|date=1992-09-12|title=Evidence for decreasing quality of semen during past 50 years|journal=BMJ (Clinical Research Ed.)|volume=305|issue=6854|pages=609–613|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1883354|pmid=1393072}}</ref> A [[meta-analysis]] by Levine et. al. published in 2017 confirmed Skakkebaek's earlier results,<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Levine|first=Hagai|last2=Jørgensen|first2=Niels|last3=Martino-Andrade|first3=Anderson|last4=Mendiola|first4=Jaime|last5=Weksler-Derri|first5=Dan|last6=Mindlis|first6=Irina|last7=Pinotti|first7=Rachel|last8=Swan|first8=Shanna H.|date=1 November 2017|title=Temporal trends in sperm count: a systematic review and meta-regression analysis|journal=Human Reproduction Update|volume=23|issue=6|pages=646–659|doi=10.1093/humupd/dmx022|issn=1460-2369|pmid=28981654}}</ref> leading to considerable coverage in the [[mass media]], characterizing the reduction in sperm quality as a "male [in]fertility crisis",<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/men/fatherhood/male-fertility-crisis-six-things-harming-sperm-count/|title=The male fertility crisis: six things that are harming your sperm count|last=Kehoe|first=Lucy|date=2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/21/opinion/sunday/male-infertility-middle-east.html|title=Opinion {{!}} A Male Infertility Crisis Is Coming. The Middle East Can Help.|last=Inhorn|first=Marcia C.|date=October 21, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en}}</ref> with some comparing its possible long term effects with the fertility collapse in dystopian fictional works such as ''[[Children of Men]]'' and [[The Handmaid's Tale|''The Handmaid’s'' ''Tale'']]''.<ref name=":0" />''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg23631522-900-fertile-territory-for-change/|title=Why the male infertility crisis could be good news for women|work=New Scientist|access-date=2018-10-10|language=en-US}}</ref>
